<p>
    KrimDok is a bibliographical reference system for criminological literature. The database consists of various literature and book balances but also contains individual references of journals and collections, digital documents as well as grey literature. All references can be researched by utilizing the search interface.
</p>

<div class="panel panel-default">
    <div class="panel-heading">
        <a data-toggle="collapse" href="#history">
            <h4 class="panel-title">
                Historical development
            </h4>
        </A>
    </div>
    <div id="history" class="panel-collapse collapse">
        <div class="panel-body">
            <p>
                Since 1990, KrimDok is being established as a digital reference system for criminological literature, in the beginning as a CD-ROM, since 1999 online. It is the electronic successor of the “Heidelberg documentation of criminological literature in the German language”, which was a collection of flashcards established between 1963 and 1989. For decades the Institute for Criminology at the University of Tübingen (formerly under Prof. Dr. Hans-Jürgen Kerner, currently under his successor Prof. Dr. Jörg Kinzig) as well as the Institute for Criminology at the University of Heidelberg (Prof. Dr. Dieter Dölling) collaborated to index journals for KrimDok. Until 1998 the Police college in Villingen-Schwenningen (Prof. Dr. Thomas Feltes) was involved as well in registering literature for KrimDok.
            </p>
            <p>
                Up to the end of 2013, KrimDok mainly registered monographs from the collection of criminological literature in Tübingen. This includes the collection of the Institute for Criminology as well as its library, but also literature from the special collection criminology of the university library. References for which there was no physical copy available at the University of Tübingen (for example digital sources without access license) were only included very rarely. Since 2014 the German Research Foundation is sponsoring the Criminological Information Service and a new strategy was applied: Now all monographs relevant to criminology are being referenced in KrimDok, regardless of their availability in Tübingen, with the aim to make the collection as comprehensive as possible. The content of the reference system hence evolved from being a reference system for locally available hard copies to a bibliographical database covering multiple sources and collections. Due to the former special collection Criminology (Sondersammelgebiet Kriminologie, SSG Criminology) and the current Criminological Information Service (Fachinformationsdienst Kriminologie, FID Criminology), one of the largest collections of criminological research was created in Tübingen. In this light, for many of the references there are still hard copies available in Tübingen, which can be used locally or ordered via the interlibrary system.
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

